          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
    Skepticism over peace in Africa
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
      Summary: Despite the optimism, the peace agreement between the DRC and Rwanda remains vulnerable. </strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          On June 27, the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) and Rwanda signed a peace agreement in Washington, offering <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #102341; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-8-jul-25-analysis-h1-8-a-fragile-pause" target="_blank">a fragile pause</a> in a brutal conflict in eastern Congo. The agreement aims to halt the fighting, respect borders, and encourage the judicial trade of minerals. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      The conflict centers on the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #102341; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-8-jul-25-analysis-h1-9-m23-rebel-group" target="_blank">M23 rebel group</a>, which has been advancing in the region and is believed to receive support from Rwanda. While the agreement brought brief optimism, previous agreements have shown that the fighting could resume at any time.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The M23 has previously stated that it is not bound by any agreement Rwanda might make with the DRC. While their expansion into newer territories has slowed down since March, the rebels are still active and continue clashing with pro-DRC armed groups. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      Talks between M23 and the DRC in Doha are not progressing due to procedural disputes and deep mistrust. International pressure from the US and Qatar helped push the agreement, but lasting peace is likely to lie with the African Union's leadership. However, the Union’s <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #102341; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-8-jul-25-analysis-h1-10-unity-is-weak" target="_blank">unity is weak</a>, and regional rivalries complicate the mediation process.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
     Experts say peace will work if Rwanda ends all support to M23 and Kinshasa resolves concerns from the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #102341; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-8-jul-25-analysis-h1-11-tutsi-community" target="_blank">Tutsi community</a>, who feel excluded and threatened. They also advocate for both sides to find a middle ground for reintegrating rebel fighters.
          </p>
         
        </mj-text>
