          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
   Why did Russia recognize the Taliban rule? 
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/taliban-ambassador-gul-hassan-presents-credentials-russia.jpg" alt="Taliban’s newly appointed ambassador, Gul Hassan Hassan presented his credentials to Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Andrey Rudenko in Moscow" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>Taliban’s newly appointed ambassador, Gul Hassan Hassan presented his credentials to Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Andrey Rudenko in Moscow. Credits: Foreign Ministry of Afghanistan</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       The Taliban announced that Russia is the first country <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #102341; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-8-jul-25-foundations-h1-17-to-officially-recognize" target="_blank">to officially recognize</a> its government. Russia stated that the move will facilitate closer cooperation between the two countries on security, drug control, and trade. Moscow had earlier removed the Taliban from their list of terrorist organizations and accepted an ambassador from their government. </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       By recognizing the Taliban, Moscow aims to gain influence in the region. They were the first to set up a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #102341; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-8-jul-25-foundations-h1-18-business-office-in-kabul" target="_blank">business office in Kabul</a> after the Taliban took power. Russia also plans to use Afghanistan as a key route for its <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #102341; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-8-jul-25-foundations-h1-19-gas-exports-to-southeast-asia" target="_blank">gas exports to Southeast Asia</a>. However, for the gas exports plan to be viable, the Taliban must stabilize domestic security, improve ties with Pakistan, and hope that Pakistan and India strengthen their often tense relations. </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      Russia’s recognition has drawn criticism from human rights groups, who say it is prioritizing strategic interests over human rights, as the Taliban continues to face global criticism for restricting women’s freedoms. The Taliban gained back power in 2021 after the then-Afghan President, Ashraf Ghani, left the country and his government collapsed. Since then, the Taliban has enforced a harsh version of Islamic law, leading to global isolation.</p>

        </mj-text>
